Hi @max5555!

The issue, I think, is that tables stop resizing once they can't wrap the longest word in the content. So if you add the following CSS the text can wrap and keep the table from overflowing ([demo](https://jsfiddle.net/Mottie/mcn8o3yu/7/)):

```css
td, th {
  white-space: pre-wrap;
  word-break: break-all;
}
```

I think you should be able to use `text-overflow: ellipsis`, but I think it requires you to set a max width on the table column - [here is an example](http://jsbin.com/soqufiguca/1/edit?html,output), but it isn't exactly the same issue as this one - I've tried different methods to get the ellipsis to work without setting a width but I haven't been successful.

if you want an image, use an image? just set the appropriate tags.. so if using an image specify alt or title or something.. (accessibility dictates you should be doing this anyways) then just pass that to the parser via textExtraction instead of having it parse the html

```
        textExtraction: {
          3: function(node) { return $(node).find("img").attr("alt"); }
        },
```

or if you have a combo of images and non images.. you can detect this and just return the relevant thing..:
```
        textExtraction: {
            3: function(node) { if ($("img[alt]", node).length > 0) {
                                    return $("img[alt]", node).eq(0).attr("alt");
                                } else {
                                    return $(node).text();
                                }
                              },
      },
```

Hi @DaveGahan!

I apologize, for the [`sortReset` method](https://mottie.github.io/tablesorter/docs/#sortreset-method), the documentation currently states:

> Use this method to reset the table to it's initial unsorted state

Which may be confusing since the sort reset always sets the table into an unsorted state.

To set the sort to `[[1, 1]]` use the [`sorton` method](https://mottie.github.io/tablesorter/docs/#sorton). 

Also, it is not necessary to trigger a [`search`](https://mottie.github.io/tablesorter/docs/#search) followed by a [`filterReset`](https://mottie.github.io/tablesorter/docs/#filterreset) because triggering a  `search` with a `false` parameter will apply the current filters contained in the inputs, then immediately clear the filters.

Try this instead:

```js
function raz(){
  $("table").trigger('filterReset');
  $("table").trigger('sorton', [ [[1, 1]] ]);
}
```

