I feel like we don't _have_ to call these reducers. This library can be used outside of a redux setup (though we'll make them all pure functions with immutable data types anyways).

Let's walk through using the API and see how it looks / works:

```js
import { appendOutput, outputFromMessage  } from "@nteract/records"

let outputs = [];

channels.subscribe(msg => {
  const output = outputFromMessage(msg);
  outputs = appendOutput(outputs, output)
}
```

From the immer docs, it seems like we should have the produce call happen as "high up" as possible, so maybe we provide mutable APIs 😬 😱 and use it like this:

```js
import { mutate, outputFromMessage  } from "@nteract/records"

let outputs = [];

// Same signature of appendOutput because of immer handling a function's length directly
appendOutput = produce(mutate.appendOutput)

channels.subscribe(msg => {
  const output = outputFromMessage(msg);
  outputs = appendOutput(outputs, output);
}
```

```js
import { mutate } from "@nteract/records";

// If we had a batch of outputs to deal with
produce(draft => {
  draft.outputs = batchOutputs.reduce(
    // For each output in the batch, append it to the prior collection of `outputs`
    mutate.appendOutput,
    // Use the prior outputs
    draft.outputs
  )
})
```

