@sscirrus A LetsEncrypt certificate counts as "real", yes (by which I mean: will be trusted by most browsers).

The reason I asked is because out-of-the-box no client is going to trust a connection to a server with a self-signed certificate. With a LetsEncrypt cert, although you'll have to replace it on the server every 3 months the clients shouldn't need an upgrade until LetsEncrypt root certificate is compromised ;)

Also, you should be upgrading the clients' OS regularly, which will pull in any certificate-bundle changes on most distributions.

